Bob,

I&#39;ve seen several pieces that were nontraditionally made that had hada, 
interesting hamons, etc.,.  There were some interesting comments in
one of Kapp&#39;s books about how some of these were made with wrought iron 
from train rails.

One other thing to look for is nie - no nie usually means not 
traditionally made.

rkg
(Richard George)

bob griffis wrote:

&gt;I&#39;m asking because I have a blade which has all the hallmarks of a 
&gt;traditionally made blade--Masame hada, a well defined and unusual hamon, 
&gt;an 8.5&quot; nakago with taka no ha yasurime and signature.  It is longer 
&gt;than most WWII blades (ha is 26.75&quot;).  It also has a Showa cherry 
&gt;blossom stamp.  The polisher said it was a folded blade (19 folds), 
&gt;confirmed by CAT scan, and was one of the hardest blades to polish he 
&gt;had come across.  Lacking the Showa stamp, they believed its 
&gt;craftsmanship indicated a pre 1860s blade
&gt;
&gt;Its matching saya is also unusual--it is covered in a tan-colored same 
&gt;which is 3 skins expertly applied, but the gunto mount looks hacked in 
&gt;as if retrofitted later.
&gt;
&gt;So, absent the Showa stamp, both blade and saya suggest an ancestoral 
&gt;blade that was stamped and refitted as gunto for use in WWII.  What else 
&gt;might I look for to authenticate it?
&gt;
&gt;nihontochicken wrote:
&gt;  
